<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870925-0149 </DOCNO><HL> Hong Kong's Trade Surplus</HL><DD> 09/25/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> FRESTMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><DATELINE> HONG KONG  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hong Kong's trade surplus widened to 2.77 billion Hong Kong dollars ($355.7 million) in August from 1.93 billion dollars a year earlier, the government said in a provisional report.    Domestic exports rose 25% from a year earlier, to 18.56 billion dollars ($2.38 billion), while re-exports -- shipments of goods assembled from parts made elsewhere -- increased 52%, to 16.15 billion dollars. Total exports, at 34.71 billion dollars, were up 37% from the year before.    Imports grew 36%, to 31.93 billion dollars.    In 1987's first eight months, Hong Kong's trade was in deficit by 1.51 billion dollars, down from a 2.32 billion-dollar deficit a year earlier. Total exports rose 40%, to 235.87 billion dollars, while imports increased 39%, to 237.38 billion dollars. </TEXT></DOC>